Sunspots: NNS vs.Â KERAS

Intro

We are comparing RMSE of various 10 year predictions (120 observations) for the sunspot.month dataset in R using KERAS LSTM and NNS.ARMA.

Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) Models

LSTMs are quite useful in time series prediction tasks involving autocorrelation, the presence of correlation between the time series and lagged versions of itself, because of their ability to maintain state and recognize patterns over the length of the time series.

In normal (or âstatelessâ) mode, KERAS shuffles the samples, and the dependencies between the time series and the lagged version of itself are lost. However, when run in âstatefulâ mode, we can often get high accuracy results by leveraging the autocorrelations present in the time series.

KERAS LSTM description and example with accompanying code (lots of it!) available via the following link: https://www.business-science.io/timeseries-analysis/2018/04/18/keras-lstm-sunspots-time-series-prediction.html

NNS.ARMA

NNS in its forecasting routine NNS.ARMA also maintains the dependencies between the time series and lagged values of itself, and then uses these dependencies in a regression (either linear or nonlinear).
See here for a description: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/327495856_Forecasting

Install the Latest Version of NNS

library(devtools); install_github('OVVO-Financial/NNS', ref = "NNS-Beta-Version")

Step 1: Create the Subsets of sunspot.month

We need to align dates to the KERAS example, so we create an xts object to manipulate the dates and verify they match.

library(xts)
## Warning: package 'xts' was built under R version 3.5.3
## Warning: package 'zoo' was built under R version 3.5.3
library(zoo)


sunspots_xts <- as.xts(sunspot.month)

tmp <- tempfile()

write.zoo(sunspots_xts, sep = ",", file = tmp)

sun <- read.zoo(tmp, sep = ",", FUN = as.yearmon)

sun_xts <- as.xts(sun)

# Create the same end date for all slices
dates=c("/18081202","/18290102","/18490202","/18690302","/18890402",
        "/19090502","/19290602","/19490702","/19690802","/19890902","/20091002")

Slice=list()

for(i in 1:11){
  Slice[[paste0("Slice_",i)]] = sun_xts[dates[i]]
  print(tail(Slice[[i]],1))
}

Step 2: Determine the seasonality

Hereâs the general procedure on a single Slice.

We use a mod(12) call on the generated seasonal periods from NNS.seas to find the nearest logical annual cycle data point. We limit it to the first 10 unique observations for our combinatorial search and store it under variable a.

a=NNS.seas(Slice[[11]][1:(length(Slice[[11]])-120)])$all.periods$Period

plus = a+(12-a%%12)
minus = a-a%%12

periods = unique(c(rbind(minus,plus)))[1:10]
periods
##  [1] 636 648 684 696 624 468 480 672 408 420

Step 3: Determine the Optimal Parameters

The NNS.ARMA.optim routine checks various parameter combinations in order to best fit the training set. We store this under variable b.

b=NNS.ARMA.optim(variable = Slice[[11]],
               training.set = (length(Slice[[11]])-120),
               seasonal.factor = periods,
               method = 'comb')

b
## $periods
## [1] 636 648 408
## 
## $SSE
## [1] 109350.9
## 
## $method
## [1] "lin"

Step 4: Implement the Optimal Parameters

We use b parameters in the NNS.ARMA function:

nns.predict=NNS.ARMA(Slice[[11]], h=120, training.set = (length(Slice[[11]])-120),
                     method = b$method, seasonal.factor = b$periods)

Step 5: Calculate NNS RMSE

The performance measure used is the root mean squared error.

sqrt(mean((nns.predict - tail(Slice[[11]],120))^2))
## [1] 30.18704

Step 6: Compare NNS RMSE with KERAS LSTM RMSE

Below is an image of the last 10 years prediction of Slice 11. NNS is significantly more accurateâ¦

KERAS LSTM Last 10 Years Prediction

Step 7: Letâs try all the slicesâ¦

We compare KERAS implementation of its rolling forecasts, to NNS forecasts per Slice. KERAS generates \(\mu_{RMSE}=34.4\) and \(\sigma_{RMSE} = 13.0\).

NNS.RMSE = list()

for(i in 1:11){

  # Seasonality per slice
  a=NNS.seas(Slice[[i]][1:(length(Slice[[i]])-120)], plot = FALSE)$all.periods$Period

  plus = a+(12-a%%12)
  minus = a-a%%12

  periods = unique(c(rbind(minus,plus)))[1:10]
  
  
  # Use optimal parameters
  b=NNS.ARMA.optim(variable = Slice[[i]],
               training.set = (length(Slice[[i]])-120),
               seasonal.factor = periods,
               method = 'comb')
  
  
  #Generate Predictions
  NNS.RMSE[[paste0("NNS.RMSE_Slice_",i)]] = sqrt(mean((NNS.ARMA(Slice[[i]],h=120,training.set = (length(Slice[[i]])-120), method = b$method,seasonal.factor = b$periods) - tail(Slice[[i]],120))^2))
  
}

knitr::include_graphics("KERAS_all_slices.png")

NNS demonstrates a 30% reduction in RMSE and a 34% reduction in variance vs. KERAS LSTM.

The parsimonious code and parameter settings clearly favors NNS as well. Run-times however, favor KERAS significantly and that is solely a function of not having comparable resources to Google! NNS is not optimized / parallelized which would enable even more combinatorial parameter testingâ¦this is a work in progress.
